      • addRow

        public void addRow(javax.swing.JComponent component,
                   InspectorLayout.HorizontalAlignment alignment,
                   java.awt.Insets insets,
                   int verticalPriority)
        Appends a new row containing only 1 object to this inspector. Note this component is stretched to fill the entire row; so the insets parameter can be used to help provide a more balanced appearance.
        Parameters:
        component - the component to add.
        alignment - one of the alignment enums: LEFT, CENTER, RIGHT, or STRETCH.
        insets - and optional set of additional insets to apply to the component.

      • addRow

        public void addRow(javax.swing.JComponent identifier,
                   javax.swing.JComponent control,
                   InspectorLayout.HorizontalAlignment alignment,
                   java.awt.Insets insets)
        Appends a new row containing 2 objects to this inspector. The identifier is right-aligned, and the control's alignment is defined by the alignment argument.
        Parameters:
        identifier - the control on the left. This should usually contain text. A JLabel or a JCheckBox is recommended.
        control - any more complex control on the right.
        alignment - how to position the control.
        insets - an optional set of insets for the control.

      • addRow

        public void addRow(javax.swing.JComponent identifier,
                   RowLayout.ComponentCluster controls)
        Appends a new row to this inspector.
        Parameters:
        identifier - the control on the left. This should usually contain text. A JLabel or a JCheckBox is recommended.
        controls - the controls to add to this row.

      • addRow

        public void addRow(javax.swing.JComponent identifier,
                   javax.swing.JComponent leftControl,
                   boolean stretchToFill,
                   javax.swing.JComponent rightControl)
        Appends a new row containing 3 objects to this inspector. The identifier is right-aligned. The leftControl is left-aligned and occupies the remaining width, and the rightControl is right-aligned against the far right margin and is as small as possible.
        Parameters:
        identifier - the control on the left. This should usually contain text. A JLabel or a JCheckBox is recommended.
        leftControl - any other control.
        stretchToFill - whether the leftControl should stretch to fit the remaining width.
        rightControl - the element to add on the right.

      • addGap

        public void addGap()
        Appends a gap to this inspector. All the rows should be their preferred/minimum height, but all vertical gaps will distribute the remaining vertical space evenly.
